    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="section">
                <head>Letter 11: 29 December 1802</head>
                <lb/>
                <list rendition="#nostyle">
                    <item><hi rend="bold">Physical form:</hi> One sheet folded into 2 leaves (18 x 22.5 cm)</item>
                    <item><hi rend="bold">Cover:</hi> Miss Rickards / by favour of / M<hi rend="sup"
                            >r</hi> Hunt / Birmingham</item>
                    <item><hi rend="bold">PM:</hi> None</item>
                    <item><hi rend="bold">WM:</hi> T. ST[<emph>x</emph>]INS / 1802</item>
                    <item><hi rend="bold">SM:</hi> Misc MS 4352</item>
                </list>
            </div>
            <div type="letter">

                <opener>
                    <salute rendition="#indent1">Dearest Lydia,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p rend="noCount" rendition="#firstline">As I am resolved not to put off writing to
                    you till ne<hi rend="underline">xt year</hi>, I find it incumbent upon me to
                    begin my letter, or 1803 will be upon me before I am aware. I am happy to hear
                    so good an account of you; that is to say that you are plunged in all manner of
                    dissipation, this is the report that goes out concerning you, &amp; indeed your
                    own letter partly confesses it. I hope you are as strong as Hercules, as indeed
                    every young lady ought to be in order to encounter the various labours &amp;
                    dangers they have to undergo. I would not have you think we are idle here, the
                    girls have had several dances, M<hi rend="sup">r</hi> Lindsay of the green<note
                        place="foot" resp="editors"> Presumably Newington Green, half a mile south
                        of Stoke Newington. Mr. Lindsey is not identified.</note> had a splendid one
                    the other night, when they danced thirty couple &amp; kept it up till three in
                    the morning. We are ourselves just returned from M<hi rend="sup">r</hi> Carr’s,
                    where we have been spending a few days in their new house,<note place="foot"
                        resp="editors"> For the Carr family, see Note 6 to Letter 1. Whether the
                        Carrs' new house was in Hampstead or London is not known.</note> they would
                    have been very pleasant ones had they not been clouded by M<hi rend="sup"
                        >rs</hi> Carr’s indisposition, who was scarce able to join the family circle
                    &amp; suffered a good deal of pain from a sore breast. She enquired affectiona <lb/>
                    <hi rendition="#catchword">tely</hi><lb/></p>

                <p rend="noCount">[<emph>fol 1<hi rend="sup">v</hi></emph>] after you. I would have
                    you to know our female book society flourishes greatly, we are now eighteen,
                    &amp; have three candidates to ballot for, the next meeting, so that as our
                    number is but twenty, one must be black-balled, we are all caballing to
                    determine which it should be. Several books are coming out now which will
                    attract attention. <hi rend="underline">Hayley’s life of Cowper</hi> will be
                    interesting[.] I should wonder tho how he could draw it out to two Quarto
                    Volumes, only that I know Hayley has a good hand at spinning.<note place="foot"
                        resp="editors"> William Hayley, <title level="m">The Life, and Posthumous
                            Writings, of William Cowper, Esqr</title> (1803–04), not in two volumes
                        but three. Hayley (1745–1820) published prolifically.</note> Darwin’s Poem
                    which he left unfinished we expect to be entertaining &amp; whimsical &amp; rich
                    in harmony &amp; wild in system like all his other works<note place="foot"
                        resp="editors"> "Darwin's poem": <title level="m">The Temple of
                            Nature</title> (1803). Erasmus Darwin (1731–1802) was eminent for his
                        poem <title level="m">The Botanic Garden</title> and was a member of the
                        Lunar Society of Birmingham, whose members had included ALB's friend and
                        mentor Joseph Priestley.</note>&#8212;Miss Hayes’s female Biography will
                    interest our sex,<note place="foot" resp="editors"> "Miss Hayes": Mary Hays
                        (1759–1843), <title level="m">Female Biography</title> (6 vols., 1802),
                        which ALB may have reviewed in her nephew's <title level="j">Annual
                            Review</title>. Hays contributed to JA's <title level="j">Monthly
                            Magazine</title>.</note> but one should read a work of that kind with
                    more pleasure if unfortunately those women who have been most fa<hi
                        rend="underline">mous</hi>, had not been often at the same time most <hi
                        rend="underline">infamous</hi>. Pericles, you know, told the ladies of
                    Greece somewhat harshly “As for you, the best line of conduct you can pursue is
                    not to make yourselves talked of one way or other” The present times are more
                    liberal to women, but still, even in England, if you were to reckon up the women
                    whose names are generally known, you would find the greater part were so rather
                    for vice than virtue&#8212;</p>

                <p rend="noCount">[<emph>fol 2<hi rend="sup">r</hi></emph>] We are going to have a
                    loss here by which the Birmingham people will gain, I mean that of M<hi
                        rend="sup">r</hi> Kentish,<note place="foot" resp="editors"> The Rev. John
                        Kentish (1768–1853), preacher at Hackney and Newington Green, moved on 25
                        January 1803 to Birmingham (<title level="m">ODNB</title>).</note> &amp; I
                    hope they do, as they ought, value the sacrifice, for he seems to feel with
                    great sensibility the quitting his connections here. You know no doubt that M<hi
                        rend="sup">r</hi> Belsham<note place="foot" resp="editors"> The Rev. Thomas
                        Belsham (1750–1829), brother of ALB's friend and second cousin Elizabeth
                        Belsham Kenrick, and preacher at Hackney. "Both parts of the day" refers to
                        morning and afternoon services, often provided by different
                        ministers.</note> has undertaken both parts of the day&#8212; We have plenty
                    of travelers now returned from France, all admiring in various ways. M<hi
                        rend="sup">r</hi> Sutton Sharpe from the Grecian antique is turned an adorer
                    of the Egyptian antique, who are now the first people In the world ^with
                        him^.<note place="foot" resp="editors"> Sutton Sharpe (1756–1806), brewer,
                        and father of Samuel Sharpe, Egyptologist; he was brother-in-law to the
                        "banker-poet" Samuel Rogers (1763–1855; <title level="m"
                        >ODNB</title>).</note> M<hi rend="sup">r</hi> Sam Rogers deals chiefly
                        [<emph>tear</emph>] manners &amp; anecdote, &amp; M<hi rend="sup">rs</hi>
                        Opie<note place="foot" resp="editors"> "Mrs. Opie": Amelia Opie (see Note 4
                        to Letter 5).</note> seems mor[e <emph>seal tear</emph>] charmed with
                    the great man&#8212; As you [<emph>seal tear</emph>] slipped the Christmas, I
                    suppose it will be a long time before we see M<hi rend="sup">rs</hi> Rickards
                    &amp; yourself at Newington but whenever the time does come, I need not say how
                    much pleasure it will give us. In the mean time may health &amp; pleasure attend
                    your steps. M<hi rend="sup">r</hi> Barbauld joins in most affectionate
                    remembrances to you both &amp; in cordial respect to M<hi rend="sup">r</hi>
                        Hunt<note place="foot" resp="editors"> "Mr. Hunt": The husband (?) of the
                        Mrs. Hunt with whom LR was staying in 1798: See Letter 1, Cover. </note>
                   &#8212;&#8212;</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute rendition="#indent6">I am dearest Lydia</salute> 
                        <salute rendition="#indent6">Your affectionate friend</salute>
                    <signed rendition="#indent7">AL Barbauld</signed>
                    <dateline>
                        <placeName>Stoke Newington</placeName><lb/>
                        <date>Dec 29<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date>
                    </dateline>
                </closer>

            </div>
        </body>
